			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2025</a> keynote:</span><br><i>Can Programming Be Liberated from the Functional Style?</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/FriedrichSteimann.html">Friedrich Steimann</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3732771.3742708">10.1145/3732771.3742708</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagM">T3D: GPLs</span></a><ul><li> It discusses general-purpose programming paradigms (functional vs. relational/modelling styles) rather than a specific DSL.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> The argument is about (re-)designing programming languages around different core abstractions and composition of results.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> It reasons about computation/meaning (what programs can produce) at the level of behavioural/executable semantics.
</li></ul></li></ul>
